  "prompt": "When should we change dusk brakes?",
  "response": "\"Dusk brakes\" is not a standard automotive term, so it seems there might be a misunderstanding or typo. If you're referring to **disc brakes**, here\u2019s when they should be changed:\n\n### 1. **Brake Pad Thickness**\n   - Replace brake pads when they are worn down to **3mm (1/8 inch)** or less. Most brake pads have wear indicators that make a squealing noise when replacement is needed.\n\n### 2. **Brake Rotor Condition**\n   - Disc rotors (brake discs) should be inspected for wear, scoring, or warping. If they are **too thin**, **deeply grooved**, or **warped**, they need to be resurfaced or replaced. The minimum thickness is usually stamped on the rotor.\n\n### 3. **Brake Performance**\n   - If you notice **reduced braking power**, **vibrations or pulsations** when braking, or **grinding noises**, it\u2019s time to inspect and possibly replace the brakes.\n\n### 4. **Mileage**\n   - Brake pads typically last between **30,000 to 70,000 miles**, depending on driving habits and conditions. Rotors usually last longer, but this depends on use and maintenance.\n\n### 5. **Brake Fluid or System Issues**\n   - If you experience **soft or spongy brake pedals**, it could indicate a system issue like air in the brake lines or contaminated brake fluid. While this doesn\u2019t directly relate to the disc brakes, it affects braking performance and should be addressed.\n\n### 6. **Visual Inspection**\n   - Regularly inspect your brakes for **uneven wear**, **cracks**, or **corrosion**. Uneven wear can indicate a problem with the caliper or suspension.\n\n### 7. **After Heavy Use**\n   - After driving in severe conditions (e.g., mountainous terrain, towing, or stop-and-go traffic), brakes may wear faster and require earlier replacement.\n\nIf you\u2019re unsure, consult a professional mechanic for an inspection and guidance. Regular brake maintenance ensures safety and optimal vehicle performance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
